05–1442":"1405–1442","1357–1385":"1357–1385","1355–1385":"1355–1385","before 1385":"vóór 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1412":"1412","1357":"1357","about 1404":"circa 1404","about 1405":"circa 1405","1355":"1355","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England":"St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England","Rainham, Kent, England":"Rainham, Kent, England","Whitechapel, London, England, United Kingdom":"Whitechapel, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1380–1412":"1380–1412","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1405–1442":"1405–1442","1357–1385":"1357–1385","1355–1385":"1355–1385","before 1385":"before 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1412":"1412","1357":"1357","about 1404":"about 1404","about 1405":"about 1405","1355":"1355","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England":"St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England","Rainham, Kent, England":"Rainham, Kent, England","Whitechapel, London, England, United Kingdom":"Whitechapel, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Donnet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  See  Dunnet  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunnett","meanings":["Scottish: variant of <b>Dunnet</b>, a habitational name from Dunnet in Caithness.","English: from the Old French personal name <i>Donet</i>, <i>Donat</i>, from Latin <i>Donatus</i> (see   Donat  ). <i>Donatus</i> was the name of several Christian saints and was popular in France and Italy, whence it may have been brought to England.","English: habitational name from Downhead in Somerset or Donhead in Wiltshire, both named from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, down’ + Old English <i>hēafod</i> ‘head, end’."]},{"name":"Dunnet","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from Dunnet (Caithness).","2  English: see   Dunnett  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When James Donnet was born in 1380, in Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Donnet, was 23 and his mother, Mrs. John Donnet, was 26. He married Margaret Cheyne about 1404. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1412, in his hometown, at the age of 32, and was buried in St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England."},"et":{"1380–1412":"1380–1412","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1405–1442":"1405–1442","1357–1385":"1357–1385","1355–1385":"1355–1385","before 1385":"enne 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1412":"1412","1357":"1357","about 1404":"umbes 1404","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1355":"1355","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rainham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Rainham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England":"St Margaret's Church, Rainham, Kent, England","Rainham, Kent, England":"Rainham, Kent, England","Whitechapel, London, England, United Kingdom":"Whitechapel, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1412":"1380–1412","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1405–1442":"1405–1442","1357–1385":"1357–1385","1355–1385":"1355–1385","before 1385":"ennen vuotta 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1412":"1412","1357":"135